title: For Sale/Trade:  Sig P6/225 9mm
postcontent:
I have for sale or trade a Sig Sauer Model P6/225 9mm DA/SA, 3.85 in. barrel, two 8 shot magazines, thumb actuated button mag release, decocking lever, black nitron finish. It comes in the box with 2 magazines. I am asking $475 cash or will consider trades. Face-to-face in Indianapolis; no shipping, no taxes, no paperwork. Must be an Indiana resident and of legal age.

* This is a German police surplus gun which was issued NEW in Germany, and has the police officer's name still in the box: Heinzan, Wolfgang.

 The SIG P6 is a more compact version of the SIG P220. The Swiss Army wanted semi-automatic handgun, that would provide excellent functionality with a double-action trigger. The 9mm SIG-Sauer P6, debuted with various new and inventive features. It utilized a single column magazine holding eight 9 mm rounds and has a 3.9 in. barrel.

 A new German police standard, in the mid-1970s, prompted SIG-Sauer to develop a new pistol that met the standard: The SIG-Sauer P225 (known as the P6) and the Heckler & Koch P7. The SIG-Sauer P225 was the least expensive (due mainly to the inventive design) and received the majority of the orders. To be able to manufacture that many handguns, SIG acquired a controlling interest in J. P. Sauer & Sohn in Eckenförde, Germany to manufacture parts. This is also where all P225s were manufactured. The only difference between the P6 and P225 — the P225 (which was adopted by US civilian law enforcement) has a lighter trigger pull, whereas the P6's trigger pull is heavier. The P225 has tritium fixed sights; P6's have fixed sights only. Because of its compact size, the P225/P6 is quite readily usable for concealed carry. In U.S. states where high-capacity magazines were prohibited, the P6/P225 is in high demand.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Leatherwood 1-4 CMR 30mm Rifle Scope W/ Burris Mount
postcontent:
Up for sale is a used Letherwood CMR 1x - 4x rifle scope. I bought this less than a month and a half ago. Very clear glass and is a very well built scope. I went with a higher power scope, that's the only reason I'm selling it. This scope has some very nice features and routinely gets very high reviews online. 

One of the best things about this scope is the 1x is almost a true 1x. It's like 1.1x so you can use this as a red dot scope on the lowest power and shoot with both eyes open and the image will not be distorted. Even the Leupold scopes that are a 1x are more like a 1.4 or 1.5x making them useless as a red dot on low power. 

Scope has "zero stop" target turrets, ballistic retical which illuminates green and has 11 brightness settings as well as a night vision setting. Has a 30mm main tube and a 24mm objective lens. Eyepiece has a fast focus adjustment. Also comes with front and rear flip up covers, 2 batteries, cleaning cloth, Allen wrench and original box. 

Also included is a Burris P.E.P.R 30mm 1 piece scope mount. Will mount to any picatinny rail. Includes 2 sets of ring tops ( picatinny and smooth), Allen wrench and original packaging. 

Both scope and mount are in excellent condition and basically look new. I paid around $330 for the scope and around $80 for the mount. Selling for $320 firm. 

I have plenty more pictures I can send you if your interested.

postcontent:
There were only three flag designs adopted, with later minor variants made to those designs that served as the official national flags of the Confederate States of America and used during its existence from 1861 to 1865. Since the end of the American Civil War, personal and official use of Confederate flags and of flags derived from these has continued under some controversy. But what isn't a controversy these days?

The display of the Confederate flag is a highly controversial topic generally because of disagreement over its symbolism. Supporters of the flag view it as a symbol of southern heritage and the independence of the distinct cultural tradition of the South from the North. I was hesitant to put these up but got so many responses on the Colorado Gadsden that I figured this may have a niche as well. title: For Sale/Trade:  Sauer 38H Nazi Pistol A great piece of WW2 history  NAZI EAGLE STAMPED!
postcontent: The Sauer 38H or often just H was a small semi-automatic pistol made in Nazi Germany from 1938 until just after the end of World War II by J. P. Sauer & Sohn, then based in Suhl, Germany. The "H" in the model number denotes "hammerless"—the pistol uses an internal hammer. Marked as 7.65 cal.    It was produced between 1939–45. The model 38H was used by German armed forces such as the Luftwaffe, as well as police forces in numbers nearly equal to the Walther PPK. THIS PISTOL HAS THE German Wehrmacht MARKS (MILITARY) !The Sauer 38H was produced for military, police, and the commercial market. I believe it to be the third variation according to the serial number.  It is a nice piece of NAZI history from WW2.  It is a used pistol that is around 74 years old.  The finish is not great  but the bore is in excellent shape.
